{"ts": "2026-06-07T22:36:42.153902+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: e39e158f2cced5a68cc724fd8a0d51b0f066d064)", "id": "lc_528b9937-7c01-4fa4-ad53-38f1fe5c15ba"}, {"type": "text", "text": "name: CI\n\non:\n  push:\n    branches: [ \"main\" ]\n  pull_request:\n    branches: [ \"main\" ]\n\npermissions:\n  contents: read\n\njobs:\n  build:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v3\n      - name: Set up JDK\n        uses: actions/setup-java@v3\n        with:\n          java-version: '21'\n          distribution: 'adopt'\n      - name: Lint\n        uses: gradle/gradle-build-action@67421db6bd0bf253fb4bd25b31ebb98943c375e1\n        with:\n          arguments: checkFormat\n      - name: Test\n        uses: gradle/gradle-build-action@67421db6bd0bf253fb4bd25b31ebb98943c375e1\n        with:\n          arguments: test\n", "id": "lc_0bbbe54c-7d5e-466a-a281-5c2427145559"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "733c4d4b-6ae0-4729-bf37-651b18de0707", "tool_call_id": "call_2dd59d3df2ce404ba810cbbf", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T22:36:55.216638+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed. Let me provide a comprehensive explanation.\n\n---\n\n## How Testing is Organized in This Template\n\nThis Spring Boot Java template uses **JUnit 5 tags** and **Gradle's `testing` suite API** to organize tests into distinct categories. Here's the full picture:\n\n### 1. Tag-Based Test Classification\n\nThe `build.gradle` defines three named JUnit 5 tags that partition the test space:\n\n| Tag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `develop` | Local-only / developer convenience tests (e.g., smoke tests against a real dev environment) |\n| `restdocs` | REST API documentation tests (Spring REST Docs / AsciiDoc snippets) |\n| `context` | Application-context / integration tests that boot up Spring beans |\n\nAny test **without** one of these tags is implicitly a regular unit test.\n\n### 2. Named Test Tasks\n\nThe `testing.suites` block in `build.gradle` defines **four Gradle test tasks**, each wired to specific tag filters:\n\n| Task | Tag Filter | Group |\n|---|---|---|\n| **`unitTest`** | **Excludes** `develop`, `context`, and `restdocs` — runs only plain unit tests | verification |\n| **`contextTest`** | **Includes** only `context` — runs Spring-context/integration tests | verification |\n| **`restDocsTest`** | **Includes** only `restdocs` — runs REST documentation tests | verification |\n| **`developTest`** | **Includes** only `develop` — runs developer-only tests | verification |\n\nThe `restDocsTest` task is also a dependency of the `asciidoctor` task, so generating API docs automatically triggers the REST Docs tests first.\n\n### 3. The Default `test` Task (CI-Oriented)\n\nThe plain `test` task — the one Gradle runs by default — is configured with:\n\n```groovy\ntest {\n    useJUnitPlatform {\n        excludeTags 'develop', 'restdocs'\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis means it runs **unit tests + context tests**, but **skips** `develop` and `restdocs` tests. This is exactly what CI calls.\n\n### 4. CI vs. Develop Execution\n\n**In CI** (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`):\n\n```yaml\n- name: Test\n  uses: gradle/gradle-build-action@...\n  with:\n    arguments: test\n```\n\nCI runs `gradle test`, which:\n- ✅ Runs **unit tests** (no tags)\n- ✅ Runs **context tests** (tag: `context`)\n- ❌ Excludes `develop` tests — these may depend on local infrastructure or credentials not available in CI\n- ❌ Excludes `restdocs` tests — these are reserved for the separate `asciidoctor` doc-generation pipeline\n\n**For local development**, a developer can run any of the finer-grained tasks:\n\n```bash\n./gradlew unitTest          # just unit tests\n./gradlew contextTest       # just Spring context tests\n./gradlew developTest       # just develop-tagged tests\n./gradlew restDocsTest      # just REST docs tests\n```\n\n### 5. Summary Diagram\n\n```\nAll Tests\n├── (no tag)          → unitTest        ─┐\n├── @context          → contextTest       ├→ included in `test` (CI)\n├── @restdocs         → restDocsTest    ──→ excluded from `test`; triggered by `asciidoctor`\n└── @develop          → developTest     ──→ excluded from `test`; local dev only\n```\n\nThe key design insight is that **CI runs a safe, fast subset** (unit + context), while **develop-tagged tests are explicitly shielded from CI** to avoid false failures from environment-specific setups. REST docs tests live in their own track, only running when documentation is being generated.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1125, "prompt_tokens": 7665, "total_tokens": 8790, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 288, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 7296, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0003870888, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 7.20888e-05, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.000315}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780871802-edWlbqpvcq1HRZuE352k", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea43b-2d2a-7521-976f-510580b7b7d9-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 7665, "output_tokens": 1125, "total_tokens": 8790, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 7296}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 288}}}}]}}}
